At first I thought setReading was duplicated, but it needs to appear twice in the code, because each occasion needs to cast the result to a different type.
If it's signed, should it be int8_t instead of uint8_t here?
actually, it should be uint8_t since `setReading` take in uint8_t.
OK. I can't see the setReading() prototype from here, so assuming that's the right thing to do.
Lines 260 and 268 seem to repeat a lot of text. It might be worth storing the result of std::clamp in a temporary, in order to move it out of each block and commonalize it further down below.
I have refactored it out a bit.
Nice, looks good now
Nit: check whether it has `0x80`. This is probably fine as the usage so far seems to be only to determine whether it is signed.
let's update this.

Hi all,

Friendly pings.
friendly ping.

it seems like the calculation here differs from https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-host-ipmid/blob/422385dab9e5027469e516fe321f9ea7c84455ba/dbus-sdr/sensorutils.cpp#L258-L304.

Should we fix that instead? like in https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-host-ipmid/+/54929. Testing in progress.
I like the idea of the two returning the same calculation.
I also like the idea of both being the same calculation. I don't think there's a reason for them to diverge.

Maybe I need to take a look at "setReading" itself, but it looks like this is slightly different than the previous `setReading(static_cast<int8_t>(rawData), &response);` right?

Because, we are not passing in a signed integer anymore, we're always casting it to uint

https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-host-ipmid/blob/9ab2f94794c4f4ca1856d35c87abe9fa77356fa3/sensorhandler.hpp#L689-L698

I think it should be fine since all we actually case about is that the data in 8 bits. Even in the case of int8_t, it get converted uint8_t when we pass into the function.
Ack
